@remark *********************************************************************

@node IntroductionNode "ScreenDaemon: Introduction"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenDaemon is the most important part of the ScreenMaster package,
as it is the program that actually opens and closes public screens.
However, it doesn't have a window with gadgets, as you might expect.
Instead, it is an ARexx host and you can only talk to it via the ARexx
language.@{par}

You already have ARexx installed on your Amiga; although originally a
separate, commercial product, ARexx was so useful that Commodore (in a
rare fit of wisdom) included it in Workbench Release 2 and above.@{par}

Unfortunately, in a more typical penny-pinching exercise, C= didn't
supply an ARexx manual with the budget model Amigas. If you don't have
an ARexx manual, you can get a very comprehensive (if a bit technical)
guide to it as ARexxGuide in the util/rexx directory of AmiNet, or
from your favourite PD supplier. This is a document in AmigaGuide
format which you can read using AmigaGuide (WB2) or MultiView (WB3).
In addition, several popular Amiga magazines have run ARexx tutorials.@{par}

Using ARexx you can perform all the usual computation-like activities
normal in any programming language, but in addition, you can control
other applications that have an ARexx port, including ScreenDaemon.@{par}

If this all sounds a bit heavy, you might prefer to use a graphical
(windows and gadgets) interface to ScreenDaemon - have a look at the
@{"ScreenMaster User Guide" link "ScreenMaster.guide/Main"} instead.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node RequirementsNode "ScreenDaemon: Requirements"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenDaemon requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}ｷ@{fg text} AmigaOS 2.04 / Kickstart V37 or higher.@{line}
@{fg shine}ｷ@{fg text} ARexxMast to be running. @{i}(inter-process communication)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The following disk-based Commodore libraries are required, but are
part of AmigaOS 2.04 (and later releases) anyway:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}ｷ@{fg text} rexxsyslib.library V36 or higher. @{i}(ARexx support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}ｷ@{fg text} commodities.library V37 or higher. @{i}(commodity support)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

Additionally, ScreenDaemon will use the ReqTools library (V38 or
higher) for its requesters, if it is available.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TooltypesNode "ScreenDaemon: Tooltypes and Shell Arguments"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Tooltypes and Shell Arguments@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The tooltypes ScreenDaemon looks for in its program icon are described
below. The arguments used from a Shell are identical, except where
stated otherwise. The full Shell template (with abbreviations) is:

@{code}
           MA=MASTER/K, PK=CX_POPKEY/K, PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N,
               LA=LANGUAGE/K, FL=FLUSH/S, RI=READICON/S
@{body}

ScreenDaemon's tooltypes consist of three kinds:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{b}String@{ub} - You must supply a string of some kind; a filename,
public screen name, etc. For example, "LANGUAGE=deutsch".@{par}

@{b}Integer@{ub} - You must supply a numeric value (a whole number).
For example, "CX_PRIORITY=5".@{par}

@{b}Boolean@{ub} - In tooltypes you must supply one of the following: YES, NO,
TRUE or FALSE. For example, "FLUSH=YES". You can also omit the value
entirely, which indicates the YES or TRUE state. On a Shell command
line, just state the keyword without a value to get the TRUE state,
omit the keyword for FALSE.@{par}
@{lindent 0}

@{code}
    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"MASTER     " link MASTERNode     }     STR      Location of ScreenMaster program.
    @{"CX_POPKEY  " link CX_POPKEYNode  }     STR      Commodities popup hotkey definition.
    @{"CX_PRIORITY" link CX_PRIORITYNode}     INT      Priority of hotkey among commodities.
    @{"LANGUAGE   " link LANGUAGENode   }     STR      Specify language catalog.
    @{"FLUSH      " link FLUSHNode      }     BOOL     Quit when last screen closed.
    @{"READICON   " link READICONNode   }     BOOL     Read config. from tooltypes (Shell).
@{body}

If you put ScreenDaemon in your WBStartUp drawer, you should add the
tooltype "DONOTWAIT" so Workbench won't wait for ScreenDaemon to quit
before continuing with its start up.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MASTERNode "ScreenDaemon: MASTER Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}MASTER Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenMaster
Shell:     MA=MASTER/K
Tooltype:  MASTER
@{body}

When you press ScreenDaemon's hotkey, it tries to open the
ScreenMaster program, launching it if it is not already running. If
ScreenMaster is in ScreenDaemon's search path this will work,
otherwise use this tooltype to tell ScreenDaemon where to find it.@{par}

I recommend you add the READICON keyword as well, so that
ScreenMaster, when started, reads its configuration from its
tooltypes. For example: "MASTER=Work:Things/ScreenMaster READICON".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_POPKEYNode "ScreenDaemon: CX_POPKEY Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_POPKEY Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      String
Default:   lcommand lshift p
Shell:     PK=CX_POPKEY/K
Tooltype:  CX_POPKEY
@{body}

Set a popup hotkey using this keyword; when you press it, ScreenDaemon
will try to open the ScreenMaster program, launching it if it is not
already running. See your Amiga manuals for the syntax of hotkey
definitions.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_PRIORITYNode "ScreenDaemon: CX_PRIORITY Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_PRIORITY Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Integer
Default:   0
Shell:     PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N
Tooltype:  CX_PRIORITY
@{body}

Use this tooltype to set ScreenDaemon's priority relative to the other
commodities running. Normally there is no need to change this.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node LANGUAGENode "ScreenDaemon: LANGUAGE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}LANGUAGE Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     LA=LANGUAGE/K
Tooltype:  LANGUAGE
@{body}

ScreenDaemon supports the locale library of AmigaOS 2.1 and above,
allowing it to display text and messages in your preferred language.
You would normally specify the language with the Locale Preferences
program; this tooltype allows you to override that setting if
necessary.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node FLUSHNode "ScreenDaemon: FLUSH Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}FLUSH Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     FL=FLUSH/S
Tooltype:  FLUSH
@{body}

If you set the FLUSH option to TRUE, ScreenDaemon will quit as soon as
the last screen it has open closes, ie. when it is no longer in charge
of any public screens.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node READICONNode "ScreenDaemon: READICON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}READICON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     RI=READICON/S
Tooltype:  <not applicable>
@{body}

This keyword is only available from the Shell command line. It makes
ScreenDaemon read its configuration from its icon's tooltypes rather
than the command line. This is useful in conjunction with program
launchers that run programs as if from a Shell. Ordinarily you would
have to duplicate all your preferred ScreenDaemon configuration
arguments in the command that you supply to the launcher, but by
specifying READICON, you can keep your settings in the icon.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CommandsNode "ScreenDaemon: ARexx Commands"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ARexx Commands@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenDaemon's ARexx port is called, appropriately enough,
'SCREENDAEMON'.@{par}

Multiple commands on a single line are legal, and are evaluated in the
order they appear below. So if you supply, for example, "OPEN=PubScr
DEFAULT=PubScr", the screen will be opened and then made the default
public screen.@{par}

Failure to complete a command results in a requester being displayed
with an appropriate error message, unless the @{"SILENT" link SILENTCmdNode} keyword is
supplied.@{par}

All the commands return a primary result code, available in the ARexx
variable RC, but no secondary result (RESULT variable). Errors during
the processing of a command (such as an invalid value for a keyword)
return RC_FATAL (20). Errors that occur while carrying out the command
(such as being unable to open a screen) return RC_ERROR (10). Finally,
the error of not being able to find a named public screen (for
example, CLOSE "NoScreenWithThisName") returns RC_WARN (5).@{par}

No further commands on a given line are processed after an RC_FATAL or
RC_ERROR condition occurs. RC_WARN does @{b}not@{ub} stop further processing.@{par}

Remember that ARexx tends to capitalize everything, so quote public
screen names, which are case sensitive. Also quote any names with
embedded spaces. This includes filenames. The commands themselves are
case-insensitive.@{par}

ScreenDaemon understands the following commands:@{par}
@{code}
  @{"OPEN        " link OPENCmdNode  }      Opens a new public screen.
  @{"DEFAULT     " link DEFCmdNode   }      Makes a public screen the default.
  @{"TOFRONT     " link TOFCmdNode   }      Moves a public screen to the front.
  @{"TOBACK      " link TOBCmdNode   }      Moves a public screen to the front.
  @{"CLOSE       " link CLOSECmdNode }      Closes a public screen.
  @{"SHANGHAI    " link SHANGCmdNode }      Sets the state of the Shanghai flag.
  @{"POPPUBSCREEN" link POPPUBCmdNode}      Sets the state of the PopPubScreen flag.
  @{"SILENT      " link SILENTCmdNode}      A switch to suppress error requesters.
  @{"QUIT        " link QUITCmdNode  }      Quits ScreenDaemon, if possible.
@{body}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node OPENCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: OPEN Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}OPEN Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: OP=OPEN/K,TI=TITLE/K,MI=MODEID/K,MN=MODE/K,WI=WIDTH/K/N,
          HE=HEIGHT/K/N,DP=DEPTH/K/N,OS=OVERSCAN/K,DC=DCLIP/K,
          PE=PENS/K,FT=FONTTYPE/K,FO=FONT/K,PA=PALETTE/K,
          NA=NOAUTOSCROLL/S,IL=INTERLEAVED/S,SP=SHAREPENS/S,
          BE=BEHIND/S,AC=AUTOCLOSE/S

Returns:  10 if screen cannot be opened.
           0 if screen opened ok.
@{body}

The OPEN keyword must be followed by a name for the new public screen.
All the additional parameters listed in the template are, in fact,
optional. They simply give you control over the characteristics of the
screen to be opened.@{par}


@{fg shine}TITLE <title>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------------@{fg text}@{par}
Title for the new public screen.@{line}
Default: Same as name.@{par}


@{fg shine}MODEID <mode-hex>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----------------@{fg text}@{par}
Desired displaymode as a hexadecimal number, eg, "0x8004" or "$8004".@{line}
Default: 0.@{par}


@{fg shine}MODE <mode-name>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----------------@{fg text}@{par}
Desired displaymode as a name, eg. "PAL:High Res Laced". Mutually
exclusive with MODEID.@{par}


@{fg shine}WIDTH <num> and HEIGHT <num>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Pixel width/height of screen.@{line}
Default: Displaymode's nominal size.@{par}


@{fg shine}DEPTH <num>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----------@{fg text}@{par}
Colour depth (1-8).@{line}
Default: 1.@{par}


@{fg shine}OVERSCAN <TEXT|GRAPHICS|CUSTOM>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Desired overscan mode. If CUSTOM, supply DCLIP, below.@{line}
Default: TEXT.@{par}


@{fg shine}DCLIP <minx,miny,maxx,maxy>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Display clip, relative to view. eg, "-8,-8,655,527". Must be quoted.
@{b}CAUTION!@{ub} Read the @{"details" link "ScreenMaster.guide/OptionsPageNode"} in the ScreenMaster guide before messing
about with this one!@{par}


@{fg shine}PENS <detail,block,text,shine,...>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----------------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
A set of system pens, supplied as pen numbers, eg. "0,1,1,3,4,2,6".
This must be quoted. AmigaOS2 has max 8 pens, OS3 has 11.@{line}
Default: System default pens.@{par}


@{fg shine}FONTTYPE <SYSTEM|SCREEN|CUSTOM>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Choice of font. If CUSTOM, supply FONT, below.@{line}
Default: SYSTEM.@{par}


@{fg shine}FONT <customfontname/size>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Custom font name and size, eg. "Times/15" or "Times.font/15".@{line}
Default: None.@{par}


@{fg shine}PALETTE <filename>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------------------@{fg text}@{par}
Screen palette filename, either ILBM or Prefs/Palette file.@{line}
Default: System default.@{par}


@{fg shine}NOAUTOSCROLL@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------------@{fg text}@{par}
A switch, turns off autoscroll.@{line}
Default: Autoscroll on.@{par}


@{fg shine}INTERLEAVED@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----------@{fg text}@{par}
A switch, requests an interleaved bitmap (OS3+ only).@{line}
Default: Off, simple bitmap.@{par}


@{fg shine}SHAREPENS@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{par}
A switch, stops Intuition allocating all screen pens exclusively.@{line}
Default: Off, no pen sharing.@{par}


@{fg shine}BEHIND@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{par}
A switch, opens the new screen behind all others.@{line}
Default: Off, open in front.@{par}


@{fg shine}AUTOCLOSE@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{par}
A switch, autocloses the screen when the last visitor window has
left it.@{line}
Default: Off, no autoclose.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node DEFCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: DEFAULT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}DEFAULT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: DE=DEFAULT/K

Returns:  10 if screen cannot be made the default
           5 if screen cannot be found
           0 if screen was made the default
@{body}

Sets the named public screen to be the system default public screen.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TOFCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: TOFRONT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}TOFRONT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: TF=TOFRONT/K

Returns:  10 if screen could not be moved to front
           5 if screen could not be found
           0 if screen was moved to the front
@{body}

Moves the named public screen to the front, in front of all other
screens.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TOBCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: TOBACK Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}TOBACK Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: TB=TOBACK/K

Returns:  10 if screen could not be moved to back
           5 if screen could not be found
           0 if screen was moved to the back
@{body}

Moves the named public screen to the back, behind all other screens.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CLOSECmdNode "ScreenDaemon: CLOSE Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CLOSE Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: CL=CLOSE/K

Returns:  10 if screen could not be closed
           5 if screen could not be found
           0 if screen was closed
@{body}

Closes the named public screen, if possible. A screen can't be closed
when it is private, or has visitor windows open on it. If the FLUSH
switch was specified when ScreenDaemon was launched, and ScreenDaemon
no longer has any screens open, the program will quit.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node SHANGCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: SHANGHAI Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}SHANGHAI Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: SG=SHANGHAI/K

Returns:  20 if argument is not TRUE, FALSE, YES or NO.
           0 otherwise.
@{body}

Sets the state of the Shanghai flag: supply as argument one of TRUE,
FALSE, YES or NO. Any other argument is treated as an error.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node POPPUBCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: POPPUBSCREEN Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}POPPUBSCREEN Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: PO=POPPUBSCREEN/K

Returns:  20 if argument is not TRUE, FALSE, YES or NO.
           0 otherwise.
@{body}

Sets the state of the PopPubScreen flag: supply as argument one of
TRUE, FALSE, YES or NO. Any other argument is treated as an error.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node SILENTCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: SILENT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}SILENT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: SI=SILENT/S

Returns:  N/A
@{body}

This is a switch; when SILENT is specified with any other command, it
suppresses any requester that might appear to indicate an error. A
primary result code, in ARexx variable RC, is still returned.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node QUITCmdNode "ScreenDaemon: QUIT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}QUIT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: QU=QUIT/S

Returns:  10 if ScreenDaemon is still has any public screens open.
           0 if ScreenDaemon quit.
@{body}

This switch makes ScreenDaemon quit, as long as it doesn't have any
screens open. This switch can be supplied with other commands and is
the last to be acted on.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

